{{Infobox scientist | name= Alfred Ubbelohde | birth_name = Alfred René Jean Paul Ubbelohde | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date |1907|12|14}} | birth_place = [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]] | death_date = {{death date and age |1988|01|07 |1907|12|14}} | death_place = [[London]], [[England]] | residence = | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] | influences = | field = [[Physical chemistry]] | work_institutions = [[Imperial College London]] | alma_mater = [[University of Oxford]] | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | thesis_title = | thesis_year = | known_for = Ubbelohde effect{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} | prizes = {{Plainlist| * [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (1951)<ref name=frs/> * [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (1961)}} | religion = }} '''Alfred René Jean Paul Ubbelohde''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]<ref name=frs>{{Cite journal | last1 = Weinberg | first1 = F. J. | authorlink1 = Felix Weinberg| doi = 10.1098/rsbm.1990.0018 | title = Alfred Rene Jean Paul Ubbelohde 14 December 1907-7 January 1988 | journal = [[Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society]] | volume = 35 | pages = 382 | year = 1990 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> (14 December 1907 – 7 January 1988) was a Belgian-born English physical chemist.
==Education, early life and career== Ubbelohde was born in [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]], in 1907. He was educated at [[St Paul's School, London|St Paul's School]], 1920-1926 and at [[Christ Church, Oxford]], 1926-1930. He was senior scholar of Christ Church from 1931-1933. He then became a senior researcher in the Department of Thermodynamics at Oxford, 1933-1935. This was followed by excursions as a Dewar Fellow of the Royal Institution, London, 1936-1940 as Principal Experimental Officer at the Ministry of Supply, 1940-1945 and as Professor of Chemistry at [[Queen's University, Belfast]], 1945-1954. He was elected as a Fellow of the Royal Society in 1951.
In 1954, Ubbelohde became a professor of thermodynamics at [[Imperial College London]], a position he held until 1975. In 1961 he was awarded [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]; from 1961 to 1975 he was the head of the Chemical Engineering Department at Imperial College; following this he was a senior research fellow at Imperial College from 1975-1988;
==Research== Ubbelohde's research interests included chemical thermodynamics, combustion, explosions and detonations, ionic melts, graphite and intercalation compounds. His group was the first to synthesise [[Highly Oriented Pyrolytic Graphite|highly oriented pyrolytic graphite]] (HOPG). Over the course of his career, Ubbelohde wrote six books and some 400 publications. Ubbelohde was the chair of the [[Solvay Conference]]s on Chemistry (London), from 1959 to 1980. The Ubbelohde effect, which is the observation that dueteration increases hydrogen bond length, is named after him.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ubbelohde|first=A. R.|author2=Gallagher, K. J. |title=Acid-base effects in hydrogen bonds in crystals|journal=Acta Crystallographica|date=10 February 1955|volume=8|issue=2|pages=71–83|doi=10.1107/S0365110X55000340}}</ref> He is also credited with coining the term [[proton conductor]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rogers|first=S. E.|author2=Ubbelohde, A. R. |title=Melting and crystal structure. III.low-melting acid sulphates|journal=Transactions of the Faraday Society|volume=46|pages=1051|doi=10.1039/tf9504601051}}</ref> He also is known for studying life from a thermodynamic perspective,<ref>{{cite book|last=Ubbelohde|first=Alfred René.|title=Time and Thermodynamics.|date=1947|publisher=Oxford University Press}} (ch. 9: Life and Thermodynamics, pg. 92-105)</ref> and for his eccentric study of the thermodynamics of pigs. In 1960 he bought a pig farm where he raised over 100 pigs and studied them from a thermodynamic perspective.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hannah|first=Gay|title=The History of Imperial College London, 1907-2007|date=2007|publisher=Imperial College Press|page=365|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x4u4ikoj1M8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> He authored numerous books on chemistry during his career.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ubbelohde|first=Alfred René.|title=An Introduction to Modern Thermodynamical Principles.|date=1937|publisher=Oxford, Clarendon Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ubbelohde|first=Alfred René.|title=Time and Thermodynamics.|date=1947|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ubbelohde|first=Alfred René.|title=Man and Energy: Illustrated.|date=1954|publisher=Hutchinson's Scientific & Technical Publications}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ubbelohde|first=Alfred René.|title=Thermodynamics in the World of To-day.|date=1955|publisher=Hutchinson's Scientific & Technical Publications}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ubbelohde|first=Alfred René.|author2=Frederick Alastair Lewis |title=Graphite and its Crystal Compounds|date=1960|publisher=Oxford, Clarendon Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ubbelohde|first=Alfred René.|title=Melting and crystal structure|date=1965|publisher=Oxford, Clarendon Press}}</ref>
==Awards and honours== Ubbelohde was elected a [[List of Fellows of the Royal Society elected in 1951|Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS) in 1951]].<ref name=frs/> He received the Liversidge Award of the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] in 1959.<ref name="The Royal Society of Chemistry">{{cite web | title=RSC Liversidge Award Previous Winners | website=The Royal Society of Chemistry | url=http://www.rsc.org/ScienceAndTechnology/Awards/LiversidgeAward/PreviousWinners.asp | access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref>
