'''Solar dryers''' are devices that use [[solar energy]] to dry substances, especially [[food]]. There are two general types of solar dryers: Direct and indirect.<ref>{{cite book|last=Norton|first=Brian|title=Harnessing Solar Heat|date=2013|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-94-007-7275-5}}</ref>
== Direct == [[File:Direct Solar dryder.svg|300px|alt=A schematic of a direct solar dryer|A schematic of a direct solar dryer|right]] Direct solar dryers expose the substance to be dehydrated to direct [[sunlight]]. Historically, food and clothing was dried in the sun by using [[Clothes line|lines]], or laying the items on rocks or on top of tents.<ref name="FAO">{{Cite book|author1=Heinz, Gunter |author2=Hautzinger, Peter |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2007 |chapter=Meat drying |title=Meat processing technology for small- to medium-scale producers |series=RAP Publication 2007/20 |location=Bangkok, Thailand |publisher=Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific, Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations |isbn=978-974-7946-99-4 |url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/010/ai407e/ai407e18.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523163235/http://www.fao.org/docrep/010/ai407e/AI407E18.htm |archivedate=23 May 2010 |deadurl=no}}</ref> In Mongolia cheese and meat are still traditionally dried using the top of the [[Yurt|ger]] (tent) as a solar dryer.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Oyunbayar, N. |title=Mongolian Food: Meat, milk and Mongolia |publisher=Mongoluls.Net |url=http://www.mongoluls.net/ger/meatmilk.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050405194906/http://mongoluls.net/ger/meatmilk.shtml |archivedate=5 April 2005 |deadurl=no}}</ref> In these systems the solar drying is assisted by the movement of the air (wind) that removes the more saturated air away from the items being dried.<ref name="FAO" /> More recently, complex drying racks<ref>{{Cite magazine |year=1999 |author=Shaffer, Marcella |title=Solar Food Drying |magazine=Backwoods Home Magazine |issue=58 |url=http://www.backwoodshome.com/articles/shaffer58.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000816011755/http://www.backwoodshome.com/articles/shaffer58.html |archivedate=16 August 2000 |deadurl=no}}</ref> and solar tents<ref>{{Cite book|author1=Trim, D. S. |author2=Curran, C. A. |lastauthoramp=yes |year=1983 |chapter=Solar dryers |title=Comparative Study of Solar and Sun Drying of Fish in Ecuator |location=London |publisher=Tropical Products Institute |isbn=978-0-85954-158-9 |url=http://www.nzdl.org/gsdlmod?e=d-00000-00---off-0cdl--00-0----0-10-0---0---0direct-10---4-------0-1l--11-en-50---20-about---00-0-1-00-0--4----0-0-11-10-0utfZz-8-00&cl=CL1.95&d=HASH014cec3765e4a2d742eeb5a8.6.2&gt=1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150902223513/http://www.nzdl.org/gsdlmod?e=d-00000-00---off-0cdl--00-0----0-10-0---0---0direct-10---4-------0-1l--11-en-50---20-about---00-0-1-00-0--4----0-0-11-10-0utfZz-8-00&cl=CL1.95&d=HASH014cec3765e4a2d742eeb5a8.6.2&gt=1 |archivedate=2 September 2015 |deadurl=no }}</ref> were constructed as solar dryers.
One modern type of solar dryer has a [[Albedo|black]] [[Absorption (electromagnetic radiation)|absorbing surface]] which collects the light and converts it to heat; the substance to be dried is placed directly on this surface. These driers may have enclosures, glass covers and/or vents to in order to increase [[efficiency]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|author=Fodor, Eben |year=2006 |title=Build a Solar Food Dehydrator |magazine=Mother Earth News |volume=2006 |issue=August/September |pages=66–70 |url=http://www.solarfooddryer.com/Info/Mother_Earth_News_Article.pdf |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bFmZNTEM |archivedate=2 September 2015 |deadurl=no}}</ref>
== Indirect == [[File:Solar Food Dryer.jpg|thumb|Industrial indirect solar fruit and vegetable dryer]] In indirect solar dryers, the black surface heats incoming air, rather than directly heating the substance to be dried. This heated air is then passed over the substance to be dried and exits upwards often through a [[chimney]], taking [[moisture]] released from the substance with it.<ref name="FAO" /> They can be very simple, just a tilted cold frame with black cloth<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Robishaw, Sue |year=1999 |title=Drying Food with the Sun |journal=Countryside & Small Stock Journal |volume=1999 |issue=July/August |url=http://www.countrysidemag.com/83-4-sue-robishaw/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bFmmNx9d |archivedate=2 September 2015 |deadurl=no}}</ref> to an insulated brick building with active [[Ventilation (architecture)|ventilation]] and a back-up heating system.<ref name="Weiss">{{Cite web|author1=Weiss, Werner |author2=Buchinger, Josef |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2001 |title=Solar Drying |publisher=Austrian Development Cooperation and Institute for Sustainable Technologies (AEE INTEC) |url=http://www.aee-intec.at/0uploads/dateien553.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526151427/http://www.aee-intec.at/0uploads/dateien553.pdf |archivedate=26 May 2012 |deadurl=no}}</ref> One of the advantages of the indirect system is that it is easier to protect the food, or other substance, from contamination whether wind-blown or by birds, insects, or animals.<ref name="FAO" /><ref name="Weiss" /> Also, direct sun can chemically alter some foods making them less appetizing.<ref name="FAO" /><ref name="Weiss" />
