The '''Special Power Excursion Reactor Test Program''' (SPERT) was a series of tests focusing on the safety of [[nuclear reactors]].<ref name=NS>Nuclear Safety &mdash; A review of Recent Developments. Volume 2, Number 3. pgs. 15-16.</ref> It was commissioned in 1954 by the [[U.S. Atomic Energy Commission]], to be run by the [[Phillips Petroleum Company]].<ref>J. Dugone (November 1965). [http://pbadupws.nrc.gov/docs/ML0803/ML080320408.pdf "SPERT III Reactor Facility: E-Core Revision".]</ref>
== Reactors == === SPERT-I === The SPERT-I reactor became operational in July 1955, with the first tests being performed in September.<ref name=NS/><ref>W. E. Nyer, S. G. Forbes. [http://xn--h1aajahjobld1b4h.xn--p1ai/booc/criticality/reports/ref_090.pdf SPERT I Reactor Safety Studies.]</ref>
=== SPERT-II === The SPERT-II reactor became operational in March 1960.<ref name=NS/>
